ce:section.ce:para:
With the gradual mastery of the microfluidic mechanism by researchers, a variety of QDs have been successfully synthesized. Shu et al. [23] firstly reported the synthesis of water-soluble Ag2S QDs in a liquid-droplet micro-reactor (Figure 1
                     a), where soybean oil containing 3-mercaptopropionic acid served as the continuous phase while glycol containing silver nitrate acted as the dispersed phase. Yang et al. [24] combined ultrasonic technology with microfluidic technology, where the microbubbles generated by ultrasonic waves constructed a microreactor in solution. In virtue of this strategy, they synthesized ZnO QDs with quantum yield (QY) of 64.7%. They also found that with the increase of ultrasonic temperature, QY presents an increasing trend, while emission peak and excitation peak show the phenomenon of the initial blue shift and the following red shift. Choi et al. [25•
                     ] also utilized ultrasonic-microfluidic technology to realize the stripping of black phosphorus (BP) powder, which in turn broke the BP flake into BP QDs (Figure 1b). Compared with traditional methods, this strategy can guarantee better stripping efficiency with wide applicability in other two-dimensional materials. In terms of the nucleation mechanism and growth kinetics of nanocrystals in microfluidic systems, deMello’s group conducted systematical study [26•
                     ]. They combined absorbance and fluorescence detection with droplet microreactors to synthesize higher quality PbS QDs, revealing a two-stage mechanism in the particle formation process. This analysis platform can be used as a new tool to study the high temperature kinetics in synthesis process of nanomaterials [27].

In recent years, perovskite quantum dots (PQDs) have gained comprehensive attention due to their superb optical performance, such as tunable emission spectrum, ultra-narrow full width at half maximum and ultrahigh QY [34–36]. Additionally, comparing to the traditional semiconductor QDs, the conditions of synthesis method for PQDs are relatively simple, which may be attributed to the rapid reaction kinetics and low nucleation temperature [37]. On this basis, microfluidic technique has provided opportunities and potentials for fabrication of PQDs in a simple way. Researchers have made great progresses in this field. deMello’s group and Kovalenko’s group have devoted great efforts to exploring the synthesis of PQDs on microfluidic platform. They synthesized cesium lead halide PQDs in a droplet-based microfluidic platform, which combined with detection platform to analyze the synthesis mechanism of CsPbX3 QDs [38] (Figure 3
                     a). Such a microfluidic platform allows the rigorous and fast mapping of the reaction parameters, which helps to take an early stage insight into the mechanism of nucleation. And they proposed a new view on the initial formation and kinetics of CsPbX3 QDs, which will stimulate the vigorous development and rapid advancement of diverse QDs by microfluidics. Subsequently, they prepared formamidinium lead halide PQDs through a microfluidic platform equipped with in situ optical characterization, in which the formation of nanoplatelet impurities in the final colloid were fully suppressed [39]. In 2018, they synthesized blue-emitting formamidinium lead halide PQDs [40] and near-infrared-emitting colloidal multinary lead halide PQDs [41••
                     ] (Figure 3b) on the automated microfluidic platform. Importantly, the automated microfluidic platform allows the thorough screening of reaction parameters and the ratio of precursors, leading to the precise synthesis of PQDs. The as-prepared blue-emitting formamidinium lead halide PQDs exhibited a precise and stable emission spectrum (440−515 nm), while the multinary lead halide PQDs shown a tunable emission spectrum (690−750 nm) with the FWHM of ∼40 nm. Abolhasani’s group also utilized automated and modular microfluidic platform to systematically explore the nucleation and growth kinetics of PQDs, which includes three-port translational flow cell and the optional extension module [42]. Taking advantages of this platform, they realized a more precise representation of the growth of nanocrystal at a constant flow velocity system for the first time (Figure 3c), which is helpful for further understanding the nucleation and growth mechanism. In a word, the microfluidic technique provides a rapid and accurate platform for synthesizing PQDs with precise control of reaction parameters and the ratio of precursors, which will spark the flourishing development of QDs.
